inion colleague John Authers=E2=80=99 headline; =E2=80=9CMarkets Bet =0ATru=
mp=E2=80=99s Tariffs Are Art of the (Temporary) Deal <>=E2=80=9D was James =
Mackintosh=E2=80=99s =0Aheadline at the Wall Street Journal. The more frequ=
ently you try to inject =0Achaos into markets, the more markets will tune y=
ou out; the more you try to =0Aharvest volatility, the more you will dampen=
 volatility. =0A=0A1869=0A=0ADisclosure, I am an alumnus of Goldman Sachs G=
roup Inc. But I never got =0Aanywhere near thepartnership at Goldman, so I =
am apparently not eligible for =0Athis <>:=0A=0AGoldman Sachs has slashed t=
he investment minimum by 90 per cent for a new =0Aalumni vehicle that will =
put money into the Wall Street bank=E2=80=99s private market =0Afunds.=0A=
=0AThe bank is fundraising for its 1869 programme, which takes its name fro=
m the =0Ayear Goldman was founded, and follows a similar fund raised in 202=
2, according =0Ato people briefed on the matter. ...=0A=0AHowever, this tim=
e Goldman has reduced the investment minimum from $250,000 to =0A$25,000. A=
 little over half of former Goldman partners invested in the original =0A18=
69 fund, the people said, raising about $1bn.=0A=0AI have to say this strik=
es me as bad advertising=3F One of Goldman=E2=80=99s main =0Aselling points=
 to potential employees is its aspirational partnership, =E2=80=9Cthe =0Amo=
st exclusive club on Wall Street=E2=80=9D etc., with its promise of power a=
nd =0Aprestige and riches. That promise isa bit tarnished <> in recent year=
s <>, as =0AGoldman becomes more of a normal public company with power cent=
ralized in the =0Ahands of its chief executive officer, but the money is st=
ill a lure. If I ran =0AGoldman, I would want to create the impression that=
 $250,000 is pocket change =0Ato its retired partners. They don=E2=80=99t n=
eed a discount, they=E2=80=99re Goldman partners!=0A=0A=0ACiti=0A=0AI suspe=
ct that there are some creative industries where letting employees work =0A=
from home a lot is an important competitive advantage. Creative people ofte=
n =0Alike flexibility and don=E2=80=99t like rigid rules, and if your adver=
tising agency or =0Asoftware startup requires only three days a week in the=
 office while your =0Acompetitors require five, you might be able to recrui=
t the best advertising =0Avisionaries or software developers and produce th=
e best work.=0A=0AAnd then clearly there are industries where in-person col=
laboration is really =0Aimportant, and if you let your employees work from =
home a lot, your work will be=0Alesscreative, and worse, than the work done=
 by your competitors who are back in =0Athe office full time.=0A=0AAnd then=
 the question is, which one is investment banking=3F There is an ongoing =
=0Aexperiment <>:=0A=0ACitigroup chief executive Jane Fraser has told top e=
xecutives that the bank =0Awill continue to allow most employees to work re=
motely two days a week, in a =0Amove that puts it out of step with some riv=
als and the Trump administration.=0A=0AFraser pledged to maintain the hybri=
d work schedule on the executive=E2=80=99s =0Aquarterly call with the US ba=
nk=E2=80=99s managing directors in mid-January, according =0Ato people fami=
liar with the matter.=0A=0ACiti is sticking with flexible work even as othe=
r bankers are upping their =0Ain-office mandates. =E2=80=A6=0A=0AOn the rec=
ent management call, Fraser called Citi=E2=80=99s more flexible in-office =
=0Awork requirements a competitive advantage. It can be a recruitment tool =
for =0ACiti to attract employees who dislike the more rigid approach at som=
e rivals. =0AHowever, competitors have argued that bringing staff back to t=
he office full =0Atime is vital to foster better collaboration and mentorsh=
ip for younger bankers.=0A=0AFlexible in-office requirements surely are =E2=
=80=9Ca recruitment tool for Citi to =0Aattract employees who dislike the m=
ore rigid approach at some rivals,=E2=80=9D but the =0Aquestion is: Are tho=
se the employees you want=3F That=E2=80=99s a genuine question. =0AProbably=
 in recruiting junior bankers you mostly want people who want to work =0Alo=
ng hours, be mentored and do whatever it takes to get a deal done, but in =
=0Arecruiting senior bankers you might favor the less rigid thinkers who do=
 their =0Abest merger structuring in their pajamas.=0A=0A=0AThings happen=
