 <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As long as stock markets have existed, so too=
 have those who invest for idiosyncratic reasons unrelated to achieving fin=
ancial returns. Some investors may be motivated by personal utility, others=
 seek to signal loyalty to corporations, some might see their investments a=
s an expression of their faith, others chase the latest fads, and still oth=
ers simply make uninformed investment choices. Yet until relatively recentl=
y, these forms of demand-driven investing have received little attention: m=
ost commentary has either dismissed the phenomenon as noise or attempted to=
 absorb it into existing models of fundamental value-based investing.</p> <=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This Paper counters that understanding. It argu=
es that demand-driven investing can create a market for individual stocks t=
hat is distinct from noisy trading as well as from fundamental-value-driven=
 trading. This is especially so as the voices of retail investors, social m=
edia influencers (=E2=80=9Cfinfluencers=E2=80=9D), and other non-traditiona=
l, values-driven investors in today=E2=80=99s capital markets have grown in=
 volume and strength. It is increasingly difficult to ignore the investors =
who systematically choose companies to invest in based on demand-driven fac=
tors such as alignment on environmental, social and governance (ESG) issues=
, an influential investor=E2=80=99s commentary on a security, and preferenc=
es between cultural and political values=E2=80=94in addition to seeking fin=
ancial returns.</p> </blockquote> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The point is=
 that if you are buying stocks for reasons of fun or values or social affin=
ity, (1) lying to you about a company=E2=80=99s financial results won=E2=80=
=99t have much effect but (2) lying to you about something=C2=A0<em>else=C2=
=A0</em>might. Guan writes:</p> <blockquote> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I=
magine a finfluencer who tells a lie, stating that a company=E2=80=99s CEO =
is dating Taylor Swift. For various reasons, the lie appears plausible. Tay=
lor Swift=E2=80=99s many fans rush to buy the stock, inflating its price. E=
vidence emerges that Swift is in fact not dating the CEO, and the stock pri=
ce plummets. Yet despite the statement being objectively false, the questio=
n of materiality remains: is the CEO=E2=80=99s (fabricated) relationship wi=
th Swift material=3F If not, there would presumably be no recourse for Swif=
t=E2=80=99s fans who bought the stock, even though they suffered financial =
harm. As one commentator has stated, =E2=80=9Cis the test for materiality s=
atisfied in cases where market participants seemingly respond in a heuristi=
c fashion to a falsehood by defendants=3F This is a powerful possibility. I=
f something is immaterial, people are free to lie about it without any liab=
ility at all.=E2=80=9D</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Finally, recall the=
 example of Ryan Cohen and his smiley face moon emoji. In other work, I hav=
e analyzed Cohen=E2=80=99s tweet vis-=C3=A0-vis the materiality doctrine mo=
